  "summary": "An inspector discusses the suspicious \"ABC\" letter with Poirot and Hastings, noting that Mary DeLaur, the niece of the deceased Mrs. Ascher, might be able to assist. The inspector reveals that Mrs. Ascher had a difficult past; she had previously left her husband, Franz Ascher, in 1922 after he pestered her for money. \n\nThe police bring in Franz Ascher, who is found hiding in a car at a railway siding. Franz is described as a volatile and nervous man who denies killing his wife, claiming his previous threats against her were merely jokes. He provides an alibi, stating he was drinking with friends, including Dick Whillock, at the Seven Stars and the Red Dog. The superintendent takes Franz into custody as a suspect.\n\nPoirot investigates the crime scene and learns that an ABC train timetable—which lists stations alphabetically—was left open on the shop counter. This discovery suggests a connection to the \"ABC\" letter. At the morgue, Dr. Kerr explains that the murder weapon was likely a heavy object like a club or sandbag and notes that even a weak person could have wielded it. Based on the victim's position, Poirot concludes that she was likely facing a customer when attacked, which supports Franz's innocence. Poirot and Hastings then travel to Overton to interview Mary DeLaur, the victim's niece, at a large house near the village.",
